  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 성인이 …… 만들매 : '
    value: 상고(上古)에 복희씨(伏羲氏)가 팔괘(八卦)를 그었는데, 그것을 문(文)의 시초로 본다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 정(精) …… 체(體) : '
    value: ‘정일중극(精一中極)’ 네 글자는 모두 《서경(書經)》에서 나왔는데, 제왕(帝王)이 마음을 정일(精一)하게 가져서 백성에게 중도(中道)를 세운다는 뜻이다. 극(極)도 중(中)으로 해석한다. 제왕(帝王)의 덕치(德治)가 문화(文化)의 근본이 된다는 뜻이다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 시(詩) …… 용(用) : '
    value: 근본적으로 말하면 문(文)은 저술(著述)만을 말한 것이 아니고, 문화(文化) 전체를 말하므로 예악(禮樂)도 문에 속한다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 전(典)ㆍ모(謨) : '
    value: 전(典)은 백대(百代)에 항상 행할 도를 기록한 글이니, 당(唐)나라에 요전(堯典)이 있고, 우(虞)나라에 순전(舜典)이 있다. 모(謨)는 계책을 기록한 글이니 하인 대우모(大禹謨)ㆍ고요모(皐陶謨)가 있다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 훈(訓) …… 있습니다 : '
    value: 《상서(商書)》에 있는 이훈(伊訓)편은, 이윤(伊尹)이 어린 임금 태갑(太甲)에게 훈계한 글이며, 주서(周書)에 있는 주고(酒誥)는, 술을 많이 먹기를 금하며 백성에게 포고(布告)한 글이며, 하서(夏書)에 있는 감서(甘誓)는 적국(敵國)을 토벌할 때에 군중(軍中)에 내린 서사(誓辭)이고, 주서에 있는 채중지명(蔡仲之命)은, 제후(諸侯)를 봉하여 주면서 훈시(訓示)한 글이다. 하(夏)ㆍ상(商)ㆍ주(周)를 삼대(三代)라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 구주(九疇) : '
    value: 《서경(書經)》에 있는 홍범 편의 구주를 말하는데, 기자(箕子)가 설(說)한 것이다. 기자가 조선에 와서 임금이 되었다는 설이 있다.
  - key: '[주-D007] 사명(辭命) : '
    value: 외교의 글과 말인데, 여기서는 을지문덕(乙支文德)이 수(隋)나라의 장수 우문술(宇文述)에게 준 오언시(五言詩)를 말한 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 최치원(崔致遠) : '
    value: 최치원이 당나라에서 고병(高騈)의 종사관(從事官)으로서 토황소격(討黃巢檄)을 지어서 이름이 났다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 북송(北宋) …… 풀었으며 : '
    value: 고려 때에 요(遼)나라와 금(金)나라의 침략과 공갈이 있을 때에, 외교의 문장(文章)으로 효력을 본 일이 많다. 예를 들면 요나라에서 우리의 국경을 넘어 경계를 설정하려는 것을 박인량(朴寅亮)이 지은 표문의 문장이 훌륭하였으므로, 요나라의 황제가 그 문장을 칭찬하여 우리의 청을 허락하여 주었다.
  - key: '[주-D010] 빈공(賓貢) : '
    value: 외국에서 선비를 뽑아 보내면 원나라에서 과거에 응시할 자격을 주는 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D011] 삼광(三光)과 오악(五岳)의 기운 : '
    value: '당나라 유종원(柳宗元)의 글에, “국토(國土)가 분열되면 삼광(三光: 해ㆍ달ㆍ별) 오악[五岳: 태산(泰山)ㆍ화산(華山)ㆍ숭산(嵩山)ㆍ형산(衡山)ㆍ항산(恒山)]의 기운이 나누어져서 큰 소리[音: 문장]가 완전하지 못하므로 반드시 통일이 된 후에라야 크게 떨친다.” 하였다.'
  - key: '[주-D012] 문헌(文獻) : '
    value: 문(文)은 글이요, 헌(獻)은 현인(賢人)인데 서적과 현인의 사적(史蹟)을 말한 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D013] 제자(諸子) : '
    value: 《노자(老子)》 《장자(莊子)》 등의 책이다.
  - key: '[주-D014] 우익(羽翼) : '
    value: 현인(賢人)의 문장은 성경(聖經)을 보좌하는 것이므로 우익(羽翼)이라 한다. 새에 비유하면, 성경은 몸뚱이요, 현인의 글은 날개가 된다는 뜻이다.
  - key: '[주-D015] 붓을 잡고 기다리겠습니다 : '
    value: 여러 문인(文人)의 글을 편찬 정리하기 위하여 붓을 들고 기다리겠다는 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D016] 하완(下浣) : '
    value: 옛날에 시종(侍從)하는 관원에게 한 달에 휴가가 두 번 있으니, 집에 가서 의복을 세탁[浣]하여 입으라는 것이다. 그러므로 십오일 이전을 상완(上浣)이라 하고, 십오일 이후를 하완(下浣)이라 한다.
english:
  title: Preface to the Collection of Eastern Literature
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When heaven and earth first divided, literature was born. The sun, moon, and stars arrayed above form the writing of heaven. Mountains, valleys, seas, and streams standing below form the writing of earth. When the sage drew the eight trigrams and created writing, human culture gradually revealed itself. The unified essence dwelling in the center—this is the substance of literature. Poetry, histories, rites, and music—these are the uses of literature. Thus each age has its literature, and each literature has its form. Read the canons and we understand the literature of Yao and Shun. Read the instructions and proclamations, and we grasp the literature of the Three Dynasties. From Qin to Han, from Han to Wei and Jin, from Wei and Jin to Sui and Tang, from Sui and Tang to Song and Yuan—examine each era and consider its literature, and we may speak broadly of the rise and fall of literary fortune through such compilations as the Anthology of Literature, the Refined Collection, the Mirror of Literature, and the Classified Collection. In recent times, scholars have observed that Song does not equal Tang, Tang does not equal Han, Han does not equal Spring and Autumn and the Warring States, and Spring and Autumn and the Warring States do not equal the Three Dynasties and the age of Yao and Shun. This is indeed an insightful observation.

    Our Eastern Land was founded by Tan'gun in ages beyond reckoning. Though Kija proclaimed the Nine Categories and spread the Eight Principles, no records remain of the civilized culture that must have flourished then. When the Three Kingdoms contended like a tripod's legs, warfare consumed each day—what place had poetry and history? Yet in Goguryeo, Eulji Mundeok excelled in rhetoric and resisted the hundred thousand soldiers of Sui. In Silla, more than fifty young nobles entered Chang'an, passed the examinations, and won fame. Choi Chi-won's edict against Huang Chao shook heaven and earth—no lack of eloquent scholars existed. Yet today their words are barely transmitted, truly a cause for lamentation. Since Goryeo unified the Later Three Kingdoms, culture gradually flourished. King Gwangjong established the examination system. King Yejong loved refined learning. Kings Injong and Myeongzong continued to honor the Confucian way. Heroic talents emerged in splendid succession. During the tumultuous wars of North and South Song, Liao, and Jin, repeatedly did literary skill ease the nation's perils. By the Yuan dynasty, scholars came forth through the tributary examination system, contending with the talents of the central plains, their ranks following one after another.

    The brilliant Ming has unified all under heaven, the vital force of sun, moon, and stars flows complete. Our realm, with sagacious rulers in succession, has nurtured the people for a hundred years. The persons born among us are vast and refined—when they compose literature, it surges and bursts forth with no inferiority to the ancients. Thus the literature of our Eastern Land is neither that of Song and Yuan, nor that of Han and Tang, but rather the literature of our own realm. It should flow alongside the literature of all ages through heaven and earth. How could it be lost and leave no trace?

    Yet alas—Kim Tae-hyun's Mirror of Literature errs in incompleteness; Choi Hae's Collection of Eastern Writers is greatly scattered and dispersed. Is this not a profound loss to our literary heritage? I humbly reflect that Your Majesty possesses innate sagely learning, attending the Classics Lectures daily, delighting in histories and canons. Through such collection and compilation, though not equal to the Six Classics, one may yet discern the waxing and waning of literary fortune.

    His Majesty commanded the Minister of Tondok, Lord No Sa-shin; the Minister of Personnel, Kang Hui-maeng; the Minister of Works, Yang Seong-ji; the Vice-Minister of Personnel, Yi Pa; and this minister Geo-jeong—to gather and compile the works of many masters into a single volume. We humbly received this exalted charge. Drawing from the Three Kingdoms down to the present age, collecting prose, rhapsodies, poetry, and essays in their various forms, we selected those whose words and principles are pure and just, bearing fruit for instruction and transformation. Arranging by category, we completed one hundred thirty volumes, which we now present. Your Majesty has named it the Collection of Eastern Literature.

    This minister humbly considers what the Book of Changes states: "By observing human culture, we transform the world below." Heaven and earth possess natural patterns, so the sage emulates the patterns of heaven and earth. Across the ages, fortune waxes and wanes, so literature rises and falls. After the Six Classics, only Han, Tang, Song, and Yuan, and the literature of the Great Ming most approach antiquity—for heaven and earth's vital force flourished fully, the great voice completed itself naturally, untroubled by the fragmentation that plagued other eras.

    Our Eastern literature began in the Three Kingdoms, flourished in Goryeo, and reached its height in our present dynasty. Thus one may trace the waxing and waning of heaven and earth's vital force. Moreover, literature is the vessel that carries the Way. The literature of the Six Classics bears no deliberate aim toward literature, yet naturally aligns with the Way. The literature of later ages first intends toward literature itself, and thus sometimes strays from pure alignment with the Way. If today's scholars would truly fix their minds on the Way rather than labor over mere form, root themselves in the Classics rather than chase after the various schools, elevate the refined and cast out the shallow, achieving clarity and rectitude—then what supports the Sacred Classics will surely possess its proper Way. But if they labor over form without rooting in the Way, turn from the Six Classics' principles, and fall into the molds of the various schools, then such literature becomes not the literature that carries the Way, but fails to serve our sovereign's noble purpose today.

    Yet now that luminous wisdom reigns above and heaven and earth's vital force flourishes, those who are born in response to this age and proclaim themselves through literature shall surely arise in succession. Why should we fear a dearth of talent? Though this minister lacks ability, still shall I take up my brush and wait.
  footnotes:
    - 'Tan''gun: Legendary founder of Gojoseon, Korea''s first kingdom'
    - 'Kija: Semi-legendary sage credited with bringing Chinese civilization and establishing Nine Categories of governance'
    - 'Eulji Mundeok: Goguryeo general who famously defeated the invading Sui forces in 612 CE'
    - 'Choi Chi-won: Silla scholar-official whose literary talent gained fame even in Tang China'
    - 'The Three Kingdoms: Goguryeo, Baekje, and Silla'
    - 'Six Classics: The foundational texts of Chinese learning—Poetry, History, Rites, Music, Changes, and Spring and Autumn Annals'
    - 'Liu Zongyuan''s principle: The work references Liu Zongyuan''s observation that unified rule produces coherent culture, while fragmentation scatters it—here applied to Korea''s literary achievement under unified governance'
